<subSubSection id="A7CC2DBDFFC7FFECFF8DFBC4FBFFFA49" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="EF697E36FFC7FFECFF8DFBC4FE95FB09" blockId="29.[113,1089,1058,1561]" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFF8DFBC4FF5EFB89" bold="true" box="[113,224,1058,1081]" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFF1BFBC4FE5CFB89" authorityName="Boheman" authorityYear="1862" box="[231,482,1058,1081]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mesomphalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacertosa">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFF1BFBC4FE5CFB89" box="[231,482,1058,1081]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">Mesomphalia lacertosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was unknown to subsequent authors and was listed only in catalogues. Only, 
<bibRefCitation id="8B4703C7FFC7FFECFEA8FBA4FE50FBE9" author="SPAETH" box="[340,494,1090,1113]" firstAuthor="SPAETH" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" refId="ref50998" refString="SPAETH F. 1914: Chrysomelidae: 16. Cassidinae. In: SCHENKLING S. (ed.): Coleopterorum Catalogus. Pars 62. W. Junk, Berlin, 180 pp." type="book" year="1914">SPAETH (1914)</bibRefCitation>
transferred it to 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFD57FBA4FBA1FBE9" authority="Spaeth, 1901" authorityName="Spaeth" authorityYear="1901" box="[683,1055,1090,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Pseudomesomphalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFD57FBA4FC36FBE9" box="[683,904,1090,1113]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">Pseudomesomphalia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="8B4703C7FFC7FFECFC6DFBA4FBA1FBE9" author="Spaeth" box="[913,1055,1090,1113]" firstAuthor="Spaeth" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" pagination="3 - 13" refId="ref50755" refString="SPAETH F. 1901: Neue Cassiden aus Sumatra, gesammelt von Dr. H. Dohrn. Entomologische Zeitung (Stettin) 62: 3 - 13." type="journal article" year="1901">Spaeth, 1901</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFF8DFB84FF0CFBC9" baseAuthorityName="BOROWIEC" baseAuthorityYear="1999" box="[113,178,1122,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Stolas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFF8DFB84FF0CFBC9" box="[113,178,1122,1145]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">Stolas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). I have examined its 
<typeStatus id="306DC094FFC7FFECFE6BFB84FE7BFBC9" box="[407,453,1122,1145]" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">type</typeStatus>
and found that it is conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFCBDFB84FC61FBC9" authorityName="Spaeth" authorityYear="1905" box="[833,991,1122,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Agenysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFCBDFB84FC61FBC9" box="[833,991,1122,1145]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. crassicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differing only by the elytra being more black than dark olive green. I therefore synonymize it with the latter species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EF697E36FFC7FFECFF6CFB24FBFFFA49" blockId="29.[113,1089,1058,1561]" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">
<bibRefCitation id="8B4703C7FFC7FFECFF6CFB24FE94FB69" author="SPAETH" box="[144,298,1218,1241]" firstAuthor="SPAETH" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" pagination="79 - 118" refId="ref50803" refString="SPAETH F. 1905: Beschreibung einiger neuer Cassiden nebst synonymischen Bemerkungen V. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologisch-Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien 55: 79 - 118." type="journal article" year="1905">SPAETH (1905)</bibRefCitation>
differentiated 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFE37FB24FDD0FB69" authorityName="Spaeth" authorityYear="1905" box="[459,622,1218,1241]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Agenysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassicornis">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFE37FB24FDD0FB69" box="[459,622,1218,1241]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. crassicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other species by the very dark olive green to almost black dorsum and thicker antennae. These characters were followed by 
<bibRefCitation id="8B4703C7FFC7FFECFC03FB04FF05FAA9" author="VIANA" firstAuthor="VIANA" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" pagination="1 - 106" refId="ref52162" refString="VIANA J. M. 1968: Revision sistematica de las Eugenysini Spaeth con nuevas especies y catalogo bibliografico de la tribus (Coleopt., Chrysomelidae, Cassidinae). Revista del Museo Argentino de Ciencas Naturales Bernardino Rivadavia 3: 1 - 106 + 6 pls." type="journal article" year="1968">VIANA (1968)</bibRefCitation>
. I have studied numerous additional specimens and it seems that the thicker antennae depend on the size of the specimen. Large specimens of similar species such as 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFC44FAC4FF40FAE9" authority="Spaeth, 1916" authorityName="Spaeth" authorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Agenysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFC44FAC4FBFEFA89" box="[952,1088,1314,1337]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. peruviana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="8B4703C7FFC7FFECFF8DFAA4FF40FAE9" author="Spaeth" box="[113,254,1346,1369]" firstAuthor="Spaeth" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" pagination="265 - 290" refId="ref51034" refString="SPAETH F. 1916: Neue Cassiden (Coleoptera). Stettiner Entomologische Zeitung 76 (1915): 265 - 290. [Published on 31. iii. 1916]." type="journal article" year="1916">Spaeth, 1916</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
have similarly thick antennae and basically the only character that separates them is mostly black colour. Also, some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFD4CFA84FC8EFAC9" authorityName="Boheman" authorityYear="1862" box="[688,816,1378,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mesomphalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacertosa">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFD4CFA84FC8EFAC9" box="[688,816,1378,1401]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. lacertosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have more or less indicated little red pieces of reticulation on explanate margin of elytra and are quite similar to 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFBD6FA64FF01FA09" authorityName="Boheman" authorityYear="1862" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mesomphalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calvata">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFBD6FA64FF01FA09" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. calvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is possible that 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFE79FA44FE51FA09" authorityName="Boheman" authorityYear="1862" box="[389,495,1442,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mesomphalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calvata">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFE79FA44FE51FA09" box="[389,495,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. calvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFE00FA44FDC2FA09" authorityName="Boheman" authorityYear="1862" box="[508,636,1442,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mesomphalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacertosa">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFE00FA44FDC2FA09" box="[508,636,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. lacertosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="28D605B5FFC7FFECFD52FA44FC89FA09" authorityName="Spaeth" authorityYear="1916" box="[686,823,1442,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Agenysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruviana">
<emphasis id="DDA2A224FFC7FFECFD52FA44FC89FA09" box="[686,823,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="304">A. peruviana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are just forms of a single species distributed in the Andes. For the time being I keep them as separate species because this problem requires complex analysis of extensive material combined with molecular data.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A7CC2DBDFFC7FFECFF8DF9E4FC4EF9A9" box="[113,1008,1538,1561]" pageId="29" pageNumber="304" type="distribution">
